[normal]The Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament v The Prime Minister of the United Kingdom
[normal] [2002] EWHC 2777
[normal] at para 59: ‘
[normal]A plain purpose of 
[normal]the 
[normal]present claim is to discourage or inhibit 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government from using armed force against Iraq without a further Security Council resolution. Thus 
[normal]the 
[normal]claim is an attempt to limit 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government's freedom of movement in relation to 
[normal]the 
[normal]actual use of military force as well as in relation to 
[normal]the 
[normal]exercise of diplomatic pressure in advance. That takes it squarely into 
[normal]the 
[normal]fields of foreign affairs and defence. In my view it is unthinkable that 
[normal]the 
[normal]national courts would entertain a challenge to a Government decision to declare war or to authorise 
[normal]the 
[normal]use of armed force against a third country. That is a classic example of a non-justiciable decision. I reject Mr Singh's submission that it would be permissible in principle to isolate and rule upon legal issues e.g. as to whether 
[normal]the 
[normal]decision was taken in breach of international law. 
[normal]The 
[normal]nature and subject matter of such a decision require it to be treated as an indivisible whole rather than breaking it down into legal, political, military and other components and viewing those components in isolation for 
[normal]the 
[normal]purpose of determining whether they are suited to judicial determination. 
[normal]The 
[normal]same objections of principle apply to an attempt to isolate in advance a potential legal component of a possible future decision with a view to limiting 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government's freedom of movement when taking 
[normal]the 
[normal]decision itself’.
